WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6.0 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello this is 6 minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:20.000
And I'm Beth. I had my first drive in an electric car yesterday Neil. It was amazing.

5
00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Electric cars are great in theory, but who has the money to buy one?

6
00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:31.000
It's true that electric vehicles or EVs as they're also called are expensive.

7
00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:40.000
But in some parts of the world, the switch to electric vehicles has been a major success story in the fight against climate change.

8
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:47.000
And it's not just rich people switching to electric. In India, poorer workers are embracing it too.

9
00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:57.000
In India, it's the drivers of small vehicles like motorbikes, motifs, scooters and rickshores known as two and three wheelers who dominate the road.

10
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:06.000
And now over half of these are electric. In this program, we'll be discussing the growing role of electric vehicles in the fight against climate change.

11
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And as usual, we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary as well.

12
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:19.000
Great. But first, I have a question for you, Neil. In India, many different vehicles use the road.

13
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:27.000
But, which country's car market is the biggest? Is it A, the US, B, China or C, Japan?

14
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Well, I'll guess it's the US, that has the world's largest automobile market.

15
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:37.000
OK, Neil, I'll reveal the answer at the end of the program.

16
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:48.000
While electric vehicles score better than petrol or diesel cars in most environmental tests, there is some debate about exactly how green they are.

17
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:59.000
A lot depends on how the electricity is generated in the first place. And in India, more than three quarters of the electricity used continues to be generated by coal.

18
00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Nevertheless, in India, the transition to green transport is well underway.

19
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:16.000
In India's Louise Rebe, head of the Climate Organization, C, 40 cities, explaining the appeal of EVs to greyer Jackson for BBC World Service program, the climate question.

20
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
What is it about to in three wheelers that's so appealing?

21
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:28.000
I think it can be summarized in one word, and it's convenience from an accessibility and affordability and efficiency point of view.

22
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:37.000
While that first point of accessibility, the state of public transport is not as developed as it is in places like London or Singapore.

23
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:49.000
There's no metro lines or fancy bus networks, and two and three wheelers spread in response to the slack of sufficient or high quality frequent public transport infrastructure.

24
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Greyer asks why electric vehicles are so appealing, so desirable and attractive.

25
00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:05.000
There are several reasons behind EVs appeal, including convenience and affordability, being cheap enough for people to buy.

26
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:10.000
In places without reliable public transport, electric scooters are filling the gap.

27
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:18.000
That's really needed because the massive increase of petrol cars in Delhi has created a toxic and very serious health risk.

28
00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:25.000
Smog. Smog is air pollution caused by a mixture of smoke, chemicals and especially car exhaust fumes.

29
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:29.000
It makes the atmosphere difficult to breathe and very unhealthy.

30
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:36.000
What's more, because children are smaller and closer to car exhaust pipes, smog affects them most.

31
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:43.000
In winter, the air in Delhi gets so bad, they have to close the schools, sometimes for weeks.

32
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:51.000
Here's Greyer Jackson again, taking up the story for BBC World Services for climate question.

33
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.000
They're having to shut schools because the pollution is so bad.

34
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Gosh, that's hardly a solution is it. What can be done about it?

35
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Well, for India, the solution partly lies in switching to electric scooters and E-Rickshores.

36
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:19.000
By 2030, the government wants 30% of its vehicles on the road to be electric and has put up 1.2 billion dollars to make that happen.

37
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:29.000
When Greyer discusses schools shutting because of air pollution, she uses the word gosh, an expression used to show a strong feeling of surprise or wonder.

38
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Luckily, the Indian government is taking measures to improve Delhi's air quality, largely through the switch to greener electric vehicles.

39
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:42.000
The government has put up over $1 billion to make this happen.

40
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:48.000
The phrasal verb put up money for something means to provide the money needed to pay for it.

41
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:55.000
In this area, it seems India is leading the world, which reminds me of your quiz question, Beth.

42
00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:01.000
That's right. I asked you which country has the world's largest automobile market?

43
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:06.000
And you said the US, which was the wrong answer I'm afraid Neil,

44
00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:14.000
in fact, it's now China, the top's the list, showing that when it comes to green transport, bigger isn't always better.

45
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Right, it's time to recap the vocabulary we've learned in this program starting with two wheeler.

46
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:25.000
A vehicle with two wheels, such as a bicycle, motorbike or a motorbike or a motorbike.

47
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.000
The adjective appealing means attractive, desirable or interesting.

48
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:37.000
A fordability refers to being cheap enough for people to buy or, in other words, inexpensive.

49
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:45.000
Smog is air pollution caused by smoke and car fumes, which makes the atmosphere unhealthy and difficult to breathe.

50
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:50.000
Gosh, is an expression used to show a strong feeling of surprise or wonder.

51
00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:56.000
And finally, if you put up the money for something, you provide the money needed to pay for it.

52
00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Again, our six minutes are up, but remember to join us again next time for more trending topics and useful vocabulary here at six minute English.

53
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.000
